THE WAGER
THE GAMBIT
The chamber fell silent except for the sound of settling dust.
Kyboah stood frozen, his sword still raised, horror etched across his face. Davinia lay crumpled in the crater in the wall, barely breathing.
Valerius laughed. The sound echoed through his sanctuary, rich with satisfaction. His body began to shift again, becoming insubstantial, turning to mist. Within seconds he was incorporeal once more, immune to physical harm.
Saijah moved quickly to where Davinia lay crumpled in the crater. Her hands glowed with healing magic, golden light flowing into Davinia's battered body. The wounds began to close, color returning to the Imperial's face. Not fully healed, but no longer on death's door.
Then Saijah's standing stone ability activated, and she vanished from sight, becoming invisible. She repositioned silently, circling toward a better vantage point.
Alfonso raised his hands. Lightning crackled between his fingers, and he unleashed it at Valerius. The bolt struck the vampire's misty form, and Alfonso watched carefully. The electricity passed through without harming the vampire's body, though Valerius flinched slightly—focus pool damage.
Physical attacks were useless. Magic could drain his reserves, but it wouldn't kill him while he was incorporeal.
Alfonso lowered his hands.
"Wait," he said.
Valerius's laughter faded. He regarded the Dunmer with interest.
"I want to negotiate," Alfonso continued. His voice was calm, analytical. "This conflict is futile. You're incorporeal. We can't harm you meaningfully. You can wear us down, but it will take time. Time you could spend on your work."
"Go on," Valerius said, his misty form coalescing slightly.
"You want to preserve talent. To create something lasting. I understand that impulse. I respect it, even." Alfonso took a step forward. "What if there was a better way? One that didn't require this battle?"
Valerius studied him. This mortal was thinking, actually thinking, not just swinging weapons and hoping for the best. How refreshing.
"What are you proposing?" the vampire asked.
"A truce. We leave. You continue your work. The town believes the threat is ended, and you relocate. Morthal, perhaps. Somewhere less scrutinized."
Valerius considered this. Then he smiled. "An interesting proposal. But I have a counter-offer."
He drifted closer to Alfonso, his form still insubstantial. "You're intelligent. Talented. A mage of considerable skill. Why waste that potential on mortality? Why throw it away after a handful of decades when you could have centuries to perfect your craft?"
Alfonso's expression didn't change. "You're offering to turn me."
"I am. Join me. Become what you were meant to be—eternal, powerful, free from the tyranny of time and decay."
"Are you a betting man?" Alfonso asked suddenly.
Valerius paused, intrigued by the shift. "I love a wager."
"Then here's my offer," Alfonso said. "Turn me. I allow it, willingly, with full knowledge of what it means. In exchange, we leave immediately. We don't interfere with your work, we don't touch anything in your sanctum, we restore the nightshade miasma at the entrance. You get what you want—a willing convert, proof that your vision can be accepted. And we get to leave alive."
"And when the vampirism takes hold?" Valerius asked. "When you realize what you've become?"
"Then in a year, I come back, and you undo it. If I don't like being a vampire after a year, we reverse the process. If I do, then you were right all along."
Valerius's smile widened. The wager was perfect. This mortal thought he was being clever, thought he was negotiating from a position of understanding. But he knew nothing of how vampirism truly worked. A year was more than enough time for the curse to become irreversible, to bond with the soul so deeply that no magic short of the gods themselves could undo it. And once turned, Alfonso would be susceptible to vampiric influence, potentially controllable.
The fool had just offered himself on a platter, wrapped in the illusion of fairness.
"Deal," Valerius said, his form solidifying as he dropped the mist form. "Step forward."
Alfonso walked toward him without hesitation.
"Alfonso, wait—" Kyboah started, but the Dunmer shook his head.
"It's done," Alfonso said. "We leave. Everyone lives. That's the deal."
He stood before Valerius, tilted his head to expose his neck, and waited.
Valerius's fangs descended. He struck with surgical precision, and Alfonso's body went rigid. The vampire fed, draining his life, and when he released the mage, Alfonso collapsed.
For a moment, he lay still. Dead.
Then his eyes opened. They were the same red they'd always been, but there was something different now. Something hungry.
Valerius turned to the others. "Anyone else care to accept the gift? It seems a waste to let you all walk away mortal when eternity is being offered."
Silence. Kyboah gripped his sword. Saijah remained invisible. Danica stood frozen with fear.
Then Orion stepped forward.
"I'll take it," the Breton said.
Everyone turned to stare at him.
"Orion, what are you doing?" Kyboah asked.
"Making a practical choice," Orion replied. He looked at Valerius. "Same terms as Alfonso? We leave, we don't interfere?"
"The same," Valerius confirmed, clearly delighted. Two converts in one night.
But Orion didn't approach. He stood his ground, waiting.
Valerius smiled, understanding. "Ja'ha," he called into the shadows. "Come forth."
The old Khajiit emerged from a darkened corner of the chamber. She'd been there the entire time, watching. The vampiric influence that had pulled her away from the library had brought her here, to her new master.
"Ja'ha, Alfonso," Valerius said, gesturing to Orion. "Feed. Both of you. Take him to the threshold of death, and I will complete the transformation."
Ja'ha and Alfonso moved as one. They fell upon Orion, their fangs sinking into his neck and wrists. The Breton gasped but didn't struggle. He'd chosen this.
They fed until Orion collapsed, his heart barely beating. Valerius stepped forward and delivered the final bite, the one that would complete the curse.
When it was done, three vampires stood in the chamber. Alfonso and Ja'ha were at stage two now—nascent vampires, having fed for the first time. The hunger that had been building in them was momentarily sated. Orion lay on the ground at stage one, the fever just beginning.
Danica couldn't take it anymore. She was shaking, her staff trembling in her hands. She'd watched three people die and rise as undead in front of her. Three of her companions were monsters now.
She wanted to run. Every instinct screamed at her to flee this place, to get as far from the vampires and their master as possible.
Then Davinia's hand found hers.
The Imperial had pulled herself from the crater, moving with obvious pain. She could barely stand, but she was there, solid and real beside Danica.
"Look at me," Davinia said softly.
Danica turned, tears streaming down her face.
"I will protect you," Davinia said. "From everything. From them, from him, from whatever comes. I promise you that. Forever."
"Davinia, I—"
Davinia kissed her.
It was gentle, careful, anchoring. When they pulled apart, Danica was still shaking, but she wasn't alone. She gripped Davinia's hand tighter.
"I'm staying," Danica whispered. "I'm staying with you."
Valerius watched this with interest, then turned his attention to the rest. "Well? Anyone else care to accept immortality? You, archer?" He looked toward where he knew Saijah was hidden. "You seem practical. Surely you see the advantage?"
Saijah considered it. The offer was tempting in its way. Power. Time. Freedom from mortality.
But she thought of Hern and his daughter Elina, of the half-finished duck, of what these "preserved" people actually became.
"No," she said, her voice coming from a different position than before. She'd moved while invisible.
Valerius shrugged. "And you, Khajiit? You already struck down your friend once tonight. Why not join her as a proper pack?"
Kyboah's hands were still shaking from what he'd been made to do. "I'm not joining anything."
"Pity," Valerius said. But he was smiling. He had three now. Three thralls among their party. It was only a matter of time before he had the rest. And he'd heard whispers about these adventurers—they carried obsidian lanterns, symbols of authority. With them under his influence, he'd have access to nobles, to officials, to the highest levels of Skyrim's society.
Alfonso had just become his most valuable asset, and the fool didn't even realize it.
"Very well," Valerius said. "Our bargain is struck. You may leave. But touch nothing of mine. And restore the nightshade miasma at the entrance, as promised."
"We will," Alfonso said, his new voice slightly different, colder.
Orion stirred, rising unsteadily to his feet. The fever was beginning, but he was conscious.
As the party prepared to leave, Orion did something strange. He turned back to Valerius.
"Can I ask you something?" the Breton said.
Valerius raised an eyebrow. "You may."
"Where do you want to travel? If you could go anywhere in Skyrim, where would it be?"
The question was so unexpected, so casual, that Valerius actually paused to consider it. "Solitude," he said after a moment. "I've always wanted to see the capital. The culture, the architecture. Proper civilization after all these years in this backwater."
"You should visit Morthal instead," Orion said. "Quieter. Less scrutiny. Better for your work. Solitude has too many eyes."
Valerius considered this. The mortal—no, the fledgling vampire—had a point. Solitude would be crawling with investigators after the civil war. Morthal was isolated, mysterious, perfect for someone who needed to work undisturbed.
"Perhaps I will," Valerius said. "Thank you for the advice."
They left the chamber, moving back through the preservatory. The four unconscious prisoners still lay on their slabs. Kyboah looked at them—Kust, Hert, the Salvians—and felt something break inside. They were leaving them here. Abandoning them to this fate.
But they had no choice. The bargain was struck.
They passed through the library, the workshop, the parlor with its empty cages. At the entrance, they found the shattered vase and scattered nightshade blossoms.
Davinia raised her hand, telekinesis gathering the pieces. Alfonso cast ash shell, and together they worked to restore the vase. The pieces fused back together, the nightshade blossoms returned to their place, and the oppressive miasma began to build once more.
They stepped outside into the graveyard. Behind them, the door to the Hall of the Honored swung shut with a sound of finality. The magical seal reactivated, humming with power.
The password was theirs. Valerius Caelus. They could return whenever they wanted.
They had a secret base in Falkreath now, purchased with betrayal and blood.
THE REPORT
The walk back to Dead Man's Drink was silent. Dawn was approaching, and the vampires among them pulled their cloaks tight, feeling the first hints of discomfort from the coming sun.
They found Nenya still at her corner table. She looked up as they entered, and the hope in her eyes died when she saw their expressions.
"The vampires?" she asked.
"Dealt with," Alfonso said.
"The missing people?"
"Dead," Davinia said quietly. "I'm sorry. By the time we found them, it was too late."
Nenya closed her eyes. She looked like she might collapse. Three weeks of fear, of sleepless nights, of holding the town together by sheer willpower—and this was the result.
"Where?" she asked. "Where did this happen? I'll need to send people to—"
"The bodies were destroyed," Kyboah interrupted. "Vampire ashes. There's nothing to recover. The threat is ended. That's what matters."
It wasn't a lie, technically. But it wasn't the truth either.
Nenya was too exhausted to press. She simply nodded, pulled out a coin purse, and counted out their payment. Eight hundred gold pieces each. She slid the coins across the table with mechanical precision.
"Thank you," she said, though her voice was hollow. "Falkreath is in your debt."
They took the gold and left her there, alone in the empty tavern.
The town was devastated. Half the mills had closed. Most of the merchants had fled. The few shops still open had almost nothing to sell. They managed to buy large woolen cloaks—heavy things that would help the vampires move about in daylight, concealing their nature and providing some protection from the sun's rays.
That night, they stayed at Dead Man's Drink. The vampires took rooms on the ground floor with heavy curtains. The others tried to sleep but couldn't shake the feeling that everything had gone terribly wrong.
In the deep hours of night, Ja'ha slipped out. She moved through the streets of Falkreath like smoke, following the scent of living blood. She found a drunk passed out in an alley and fed, careful to leave him alive but drained. He'd wake with no memory of what happened, just weakness and confusion.
Alfonso left through a window. He was methodical about it, choosing targets carefully. A bandit on the outskirts of town, someone who wouldn't be missed. The feeding was efficient, clinical. When it was done, he felt stronger, more focused. The hunger that had been gnawing at him faded.
They both returned before dawn, and no one was the wiser.
THE SUMMONS
Morning came too soon. The party gathered in the common room for breakfast, the vampires among them looking slightly more comfortable after their nighttime feeding.
A courier arrived just as they were finishing their meal. He wore the colors of the High King's household—fine blue and gold livery that marked him as official business.
"The Obsidian Lanterns?" he asked, scanning the table.
"That's us," Davinia said.
He handed her a sealed letter bearing the mark of High King Torygg himself. She broke the seal and read aloud:
"To the Obsidian Lanterns, you are hereby summoned to Solitude to stand before High King Torygg. Your presence is required immediately. Do not delay. Signed, High King Torygg, Lord of Haafingar, Protector of Skyrim."
The party exchanged glances.
"Well," Kyboah said. "I guess we're going to Solitude."
They made arrangements quickly. A cart was purchased from one of the few merchants still operating. Horses were available, but expensive and unnecessary.
"We'll pull it," Ja'ha said simply. She looked at Orion and Kyboah. "The three of us. Should be easy enough."
Orion nodded. His fever was in full effect now, but the vampiric strength was already manifesting. Kyboah, with his natural Khajiit speed and endurance, would have no trouble keeping pace.
Alfonso climbed into the cart with Davinia, Danica, and Saijah. He had no interest in manual labor, even with his new strength.
They left Falkreath behind, following the road north toward Solitude.
THE ROAD
The journey was long but uneventful at first. The vampires pulled the cart with surprising ease, and Kyboah kept pace without breaking a sweat. The road wound through pine forests and across open plains, always heading north toward Haafingar Hold.
They were passing through a stretch of open road when they saw the checkpoint ahead. Imperial soldiers in full armor, stopping travelers and checking cargo. Tax collectors, gathering funds for the war effort.
"Should we go around?" Saijah asked quietly.
"They've already seen us," Davinia replied. "Going around would look suspicious."
The soldiers waved them to a stop. There were six of them, all professional, all armed. Their leader stepped forward—a Nord woman with a sergeant's insignia.
"Travelers," she said. "Imperial tax assessment. We'll need to inspect your cart and collect the appropriate fees for passage through Imperial-controlled territory."
"How much?" Kyboah asked.
"Depends on what you're carrying," she replied. "Standard rate is fifty gold for merchants, twenty-five for civilians."
Alfonso looked at the soldiers. At their armor, their weapons, their casual assumption of authority. He thought about the coins weighing down his purse, money that could be better spent elsewhere.
He thought about how easy it would be.
His hands moved. "Fireball."
The explosion was instantaneous. A sphere of white-hot flame erupted in the center of the group, engulfing all six soldiers. Their screams were brief. When the smoke cleared, there were only charred bodies and melted armor.
The party stared at Alfonso.
"What?" he said, climbing back into the cart. "They were going to take our money. Now they won't."
"You just murdered six Imperial soldiers," Davinia said, her voice tight.
"I killed six bandits who were extorting travelers," Alfonso corrected. "There's a difference."
"They were—"
"They're dead. Let's keep moving."
Ja'ha and Orion had already resumed pulling the cart. Kyboah, after a long moment, followed. What was done was done, and standing around debating it wouldn't bring the soldiers back.
They pressed on, leaving the bodies behind.
DRAGON BRIDGE
The town of Dragon Bridge sat at a strategic crossing of the Karth River. It was an Imperial stronghold, with a full garrison and regular patrols. They'd have to pass inspection to cross.
The party approached the checkpoint with forced calm. The vampires kept their new cloaks pulled tight, hoods up to shield their faces from the afternoon sun.
"Halt," the guard captain said. He was a veteran, his eyes sharp and suspicious. "State your business."
"Traveling to Solitude," Davinia said. She produced the High King's summons. "We've been called by King Torygg himself."
The captain examined the seal, then handed it back. "I'll need to search your cart. Standard procedure."
They had nothing to hide, technically. Their weapons were visible and legal. Their supplies were ordinary. The captain and two of his men went through everything methodically while the party waited.
One of the guards walked past Orion, close enough to see under his hood. The Breton turned his face away, but not before the guard caught a glimpse of pale skin and slightly elongated canines.
The guard paused, his hand drifting toward his sword.
Orion met his eyes and smiled. Just a normal smile. Nothing threatening.
The guard's hand relaxed. He moved on, and the inspection continued.
The cloaks had worked. The heavy wool concealed their nature just enough to pass casual scrutiny.
"You're clear," the captain said finally. "Cross when ready. And keep those hoods up—looks like rain coming."
They crossed the bridge and continued north.
SOLITUDE
The capital of Skyrim rose before them as evening approached. Solitude sat on a massive natural arch of rock, its walls and towers imposing and proud. The city was a statement of power, of civilization, of Imperial authority.
They approached the main gate and were immediately met by an Imperial officer. He wore the armor of a Legate, his bearing that of someone used to command. Behind him stood a full regiment—twenty soldiers in formation, their armor gleaming, their discipline evident.
The Legate's eyes swept over the party, then locked onto Davinia. His expression shifted—recognition, surprise, and something else. Respect, perhaps.
"Davinia," he said. "It's been a long time."
Davinia's composure cracked for just a moment. She knew this man. Legate Quintus, one of the Imperial Legion's finest officers. She'd served under him, years ago, before she'd left military service.
"Legate," she said, forcing her voice to remain steady. "I didn't expect to see you here."
"The Legion goes where it's needed," Quintus replied. Then his expression softened slightly. "You look well. Word of your... adventures has reached even us. The Obsidian Lanterns, they're calling you now."
"Something like that," Davinia said.
Quintus's gaze moved to the others, taking in the hooded figures, the weapons, the exhaustion visible on their faces. "High King Torygg is waiting for you at the Blue Palace. But you look like you could use rest first. There's an inn—the Winking Skeever. I'll have my men escort you there. You can clean up, get some proper food, and report to the King in the morning."
"That would be appreciated," Davinia said, relief evident in her voice.
Quintus gestured to his soldiers. "Show them to the inn. Make sure they're taken care of. And inform the palace the Obsidian Lanterns have arrived."
As they walked through Solitude's streets, Davinia was acutely aware of Quintus's eyes on her back. Her old life in the Legion, the person she'd been before adventuring—it all felt very close suddenly.
Danica squeezed her hand, and Davinia squeezed back.
The Winking Skeever was a respectable establishment near the docks. The innkeeper took one look at the Imperial escort and provided their best rooms without question. The soldiers departed, leaving the party alone.
They stood in the common room, exhausted and changed. Three of them were vampires now. One of them had murdered Imperial soldiers without hesitation. All of them had abandoned four innocent people to a vampire's clutches.
"Get some rest," Kyboah said quietly. "Whatever the High King wants, we'll deal with it tomorrow."
They separated to their rooms. The vampires took the ones with the heaviest curtains, away from windows. Davinia and Danica shared a room, neither wanting to be alone.
Outside, Solitude prepared for night. The capital of Skyrim, seat of Imperial power, heartbeat of a province at war.
And somewhere in the streets below, three vampires waited for darkness, when they could feed again.

